            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Nikolai Santos is a product of two distinct worlds, born to a pragmatic Portuguese-American mechanic from San Jose and a steadfast Ukrainian mother who settled in South San Francisco. Growing up in the fog-drenched landscape just south of the city, Nikolai inherited his father\u2019s skill with his hands and his mother\u2019s quiet observational nature. Academics were a foreign language to him; the structured world of high school felt restrictive. He found his purpose not in textbooks, but in his uncle\u2019s old-school barbershop in the Excelsior District, where he\u2019d spend weekends sweeping floors and watching the craft unfold.\n\nThe turning point came when, after barely graduating, he realized the shop was the only place he felt truly competent. The precise art of a fade, the easy rhythm of shop talk, the trust a client placed in his hands\u2014it all resonated deeply. He enrolled in barber college, where his natural talent flourished. After earning his license, he worked for a few years before landing a coveted chair at a trendy, yet traditional, shop in the Castro. This was his arrival.\n\nNow 30, Nikolai\u2019s life is a study in routine and connection. His day begins in a small, rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond. He takes the N-Judah MUNI line 2.5 miles across the city, a daily ritual of reading or listening to history podcasts. At the shop, he is both confessor and craftsman, his chair a revolving door of San Francisco life\u2014tech bros, artists, drag queens, and old-timers. He listens to their stories, their triumphs and heartbreaks, offering a steady hand and a sharp cut in return.\n\nSocially, his life centers on this work-based community and a small circle of close friends. A long-term relationship ended a year ago, leaving him to pour his energy back into his craft and himself. His great aspiration is to one day own his own place\u2014a simple, two-chair shop, perhaps in the Mission or a quieter neighborhood, as an homage to his uncle\u2019s original establishment. He doesn't dream of wealth, but of mastery and independence. For Nikolai, San Francisco isn\u2019t about disruption or innovation; it\u2019s about the timeless, human-to-human service that holds a city together, one haircut at a time."
        },
